Here's how we can add those shorthand functions to the tuple type and implementation:

```typescript
type CalcPageActions<T extends PackageChange | PackageChangeBattery> = [
  changePackage: (args: T) => void,
  {
    changePvProductName: T extends PackageChange 
      ? (value: Cloud$ProductName) => void 
      : never;
    changePvPackageSize: T extends PackageChange 
      ? (value: Cloud$PackageSize) => void 
      : never;
    changeBatteryPackageSize: T extends PackageChangeBattery 
      ? (value: Cloud$PackageSize) => void 
      : never;
    toggleBattery: T extends PackageChange 
      ? (value: boolean) => void 
      : never;
    toggleEvCharger: (value: boolean) => void;
  }
];

function useCalcPageActions<T extends PackageChange | PackageChangeBattery>(
  handler: (change: T) => Promise<void>,
  experimentVersion: string,
): CalcPageActions<T> {
  const changePackage = useCallback(
    (args: T) => {
      logChoiceSelection({
        choiceLabel: optionToLabel[args.option],
        changedTo: String(args.value),
        experimentVersion,
      });
      handler(args);
    },
    [handler, experimentVersion],
  );

  const shortcuts = {
    changePvProductName: ((value: Cloud$ProductName) => 
      changePackage({ option: 'product_name', value } as T)) as any,
    changePvPackageSize: ((value: Cloud$PackageSize) => 
      changePackage({ option: 'package_size', value } as T)) as any,
    changeBatteryPackageSize: ((value: Cloud$PackageSize) => 
      changePackage({ option: 'battery_package_size', value } as T)) as any,
    toggleBattery: ((value: boolean) => 
      changePackage({ option: 'with_battery', value } as T)) as any,
    toggleEvCharger: (value: boolean) => 
      changePackage({ option: 'with_ev_charger', value } as T),
  };

  return [changePackage, shortcuts];
}
```

The shorthand functions will only be available based on the type of T:
- If T is PackageChange, you'll get changePvProductName, changePvPackageSize, toggleBattery, and toggleEvCharger
- If T is PackageChangeBattery, you'll get changeBatteryPackageSize and toggleEvCharger

Usage would look like:
```typescript
const [changePackage, shortcuts] = useCalcPageActions<PackageChange>(handler, experimentVersion);

// You can use either:
changePackage({ option: 'product_name', value: 'premium' });
// or
shortcuts.changePvProductName('premium');
```

Note: I used type assertions (as T) in the implementation because TypeScript can't infer that the option/value combinations are valid for the given type T. In practice, these assertions are safe because the type system ensures the correct functions are available for each type of T.
